commentBody:
@David Johnson

You, too?

I used to sprinkle those guys in my FORTRAN code like it was salt on popcorn.

@Francis
Not only have I not used a GOTO in ages, my cardiologist has me holding the salt on my popcorn.
Two more of life's little pleasures gone.

@David Johnson 

*23456
   500    CONTINUE

@Mary

I guess some of us think corruption can only go one way. 

It seems very sexist to me to make such a distinction.

@Steven M.

Yes. 

But his inadvertent laugher had nothing to do with Kugelman's incendiary formulation here.

@B
Won’t comment on the rest which are fair reactions whether I agree completely or not; but “poison pen”
Is an adjectival phrase, as is “written with venom”. I agree you wouldn’t necessarily interchange them in a sentence, but I think they are grammatically equivalent and it’s a fair (but too easy?) clue

@B
I had no problem with OH NO REASON, which I thought was hilarious.

But I agree that this was not a Thursday puzzle, not by a long shot. I came in expecting a tricky theme and was extremely disappointed.

@SP

I perked up when I saw John Kugelman's name up top, but I couldn't agree more.  Nice puzzle/wrong day.

I did have to check a cross to see whether we were dealing with batS or OWLS, but most of the fill was very straightforward.

@SP
Well, darn.  I was thinking it would be a great excuse to revisit Italy (since I spent most of the time in Florence and then in the South Tyrol  (taking a climbing train from ?Bolzano? Memory is failing me)...    So, no clever clams, after all.  Oh well...at least a good chuckle.

Thanks for standing up for this puzzle and John Kugelman.  I am of the same mind....and I certainly would not invite that crowd to dinner....

@Patrick J.

In baseball, we usually say “overhand” and “underhand,” but “sidearm.”

Underarm is where the deodorant goes.

@Matt

No. I find it much easier to remember the ones I don't like 🤷🏽

Also, if we didn't get a Kugelman puzzle every 2 or 3 weeks, I'd probably be less likely to remember him. I'm pretty sure nobody has had as many puzzles as he in the past two years or so, and I can't remember liking a single one of them. It's hard to not recall the name in such a context...

@charlie
Poison-pen letters are written with venom.
Adnoun. (hee hee)

@SBK in TO
@Jerry
my apologies to the emus and their herders. our original anti-capitalist 😉 discussion was on yesterday's board.

@sbk in to
my god I'm a closet liberal!
thanks for nothing😆

@Beverly
What  bothers me isn't the pluralization, but rather the inaccuracy of the clue. A SENSEI does not necessarily guard the bushido tradition, since as you mentioned a SENSEI can be anything from a teacher to a doctor to a manga artist--anyone who is more skilled than you. Additionally, someone who keeps the bushido tradition is not necessarily anyone's SENSEI, especially in this day and age, when being a samurai has gone somewhat out of fashion.

I was so confounded by this that I assumed there must be some clever Thursday trick at hand. Alas, clever Thursday tricks seem to have gone the way of the samurai.

@D
But you don't hear them daily. You almost never hear them on a Monday or Tuesday, because those are expected to be the easiest puzzles of the week. And when we're given a properly difficult late week puzzle we fairly burst with joy; the complaints on those days are from those who found the puzzle too difficult.

It's a forum; people will continue to have opinions, and will continue to express them.

@Miri

Exactly.

I was just thinking, whether they are right or wrong about the complaints, this grumbling about every little deviation in puzzle difficulty is getting very boring.

@Katie I’m an experienced solver (this puzzle was 1537 in my *current* streak). I’ve been doing the NYT for most of my adult life, 30 years plus. 

I’d rather discuss the puzzle itself than hear incessant complaining about comparisons to a Platonic ideal of a Wed or a Sat. Valid complaints or not, it makes for a tedious discussion. 

So everyone can complain as much as they like. I can express my feelings about what these complaints do to my enjoyment of the social aspect of these comment sections.

@Mean Old Lady
Eh, I suppose you're right. I didn't detect violence, either, but different people have different triggers into inner recesses of the mind that are beyond comprehension. (The presence of 51D doesn't help the cause much, either).

I'm just trying to be a kinder, gentler Republican. 😋

@Katie
That's a very succinct, yet powerful statement. Dare I venture to assay that your statement should be applied to many other causes?
Great insight 👏

@Xword Junkie

We're IN SYNC.
(Which I thought was the answer to 6-Down for a while.)

@Xword Junkie

The agreement doesn't bother me.
That we're posting at almost the same time makes me a little concerned.

@Joe

BLUE is practically moth-eaten, it's such an old word for describing something rather naughty or ribald...  and then there were the Blue Laws that prevented stores from being open on (the Christian) Sabbath; no sales of alcohol on Sundays, either.

I never saw "The Wire"--that's what crosses are for...and  I am a "sometime OHIOAN" myself but that clue eluded me until I saw the crossings.  NPR's NINA was a gimme; pretty soon such clues will be considered passé, perhaps.  You are right that being a Newbie makes these more difficult, but now you're in the know!

@Gil
Well, right NOW it is.... The spoils of war.  

  It ought to be un ESTADO.

@D 

It didn't seem like a Thursday, in that it didn't have a trick that leaves you baffled until you finally see it, at which point you start making rapid progress. This one can be resolved just by doing the crosses.

But unreasonably difficult wordplay and arcane trivia? That wasn't my experience at all with this puzzle. I had to root out a few wrong answers that I was clinging to (did that a lot, actually), but I finished it without looking anything up, not even to verify spelling, and it was unusually fast.

@Bob of Newton 

And then there is the infamous "underarm pitch."

It's said to be even worse than a spitball.

@Your Fired
The validity of this gripe comes down to whether one believes the term "continent" should only apply to one discrete landmass, excluding many islands such as the UK islands from any continent. Others have argued for that stance, but per <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continent" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continent</a>, that's not the predominant view. Most people would say UK is part of Europe.

Umm... also, @Your Fired, before aggressively throwing yellow flags, check your screen name. You're[sic] middle school English teacher may be spinning [wink].

@Marlene

"I don't hate the rebus puzzles, they are just more work, and I am lazy."

Love this.

@Michael
You're entitled to your opinions, but you express three of them and claim that they are objective. They are not, they are subjective. Have you not heard the phrase "Kind of a Drag"? Have you not heard the phrase "MAIN drag"? When I got that answer I found it both clever and witty.  And it gave me an oldies earworm. I give you the Buckinghams. And thanks for introducing me to the term "phrase-mining".

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QSqg1NqBKGE" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QSqg1NqBKGE</a>

@Serge
Well, that took me down a sidetrack. A quick search shows that you are indeed, correct. 

At the risk of confusing things, may I say that TIL that TILL is more accurate than 'TIL.

@Serge

‘TIL is a contraction of UNTIL.  TILL is a word unto itself that predates UNTIL. What is not a word is TIL. 

<a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/grammar/should-you-use-until-or-till-or-til" target="_blank">https://www.merriam-webster.com/grammar/should-you-use-until-or-till-or-til</a>

@Steve L

"What is not a word is TIL"
Correct. It's an initialism.

@hieronymous

Oh is _that_ what it means? 

As a PK I was never told what anything meant. Kids would start a joke and then stop short at the punch line, "Oh. Can't say it in front of her." I used to think this was the source of all my neuroses.

@Lynn
I used to hate it when I was interrupted by having to work. The nerve!😆
That's all in the past now.

@Randi

I think the penalty flag will be overturned when challenged....  Baseball isn't the only throwing sport, after all. I hadn't heard of it either, but I never assume that means it doesn't exist.   

